  "prompt": "Was there welfare during the Anglo-Saxon era?",
  "response": "During the Anglo-Saxon era, which spanned from the early 5th century to the late 11th century in England, the concept of welfare as understood today did not exist. However, the Anglo-Saxon society did have informal means of supporting individuals in need. \n\nCommunity and kinship played a crucial role in providing support to those who were unable to fend for themselves. Families and local communities would often care for the elderly, widows, orphans, and those who were sick or disabled. The church also played a significant role in providing charity and support to the poor and needy. Monastic institutions, in particular, were known for their charitable activities, including distributing food and providing shelter to those in need.\n\nAdditionally, Anglo-Saxon laws included some provisions for social welfare. For instance, wergild (a man-price) was a legal system where compensation was paid to the family of a person who was killed or injured, which could provide some form of financial support in cases of loss or harm.\n\nOverall, while there was no structured welfare system, various practices and institutions within Anglo-Saxon society contributed to the care and support of vulnerable individuals.",
